// Example: @doc block
// Document content blocks using Markdown syntax

@meta {
  title: "@doc Block Examples";
  author: "OmniScript Team";
  date: "2026-01-22";
}

// Basic text content
@doc {
  # Heading Level 1

  This is a basic paragraph with some text content. The @doc block
  supports full Markdown syntax for rich text formatting.

  ## Heading Level 2

  You can use **bold text**, *italic text*, and ***bold italic*** for emphasis.

  ### Heading Level 3

  Inline `code` looks like this. You can also include [links](https://example.com).
}

// Lists and formatting
@doc {
  # Lists

  ## Unordered Lists

  - First item
  - Second item
    - Nested item
    - Another nested item
  - Third item

  ## Ordered Lists

  1. First step
  2. Second step
     1. Sub-step A
     2. Sub-step B
  3. Third step

  ## Task Lists

  - [x] Completed task
  - [ ] Pending task
  - [ ] Another pending task
}

// Blockquotes and horizontal rules
@doc {
  # Quotes and Dividers

  > This is a blockquote. Use it for important callouts,
  > citations, or to highlight key information.

  ---

  The horizontal rule above creates a visual separator between sections.

  > **Note:** You can combine formatting within blockquotes
  > for added emphasis.
}

// Tables in Markdown
@doc {
  # Markdown Tables

  | Column 1 | Column 2 | Column 3 |
  |----------|----------|----------|
  | Cell 1   | Cell 2   | Cell 3   |
  | Cell 4   | Cell 5   | Cell 6   |

  Tables support alignment:

  | Left | Center | Right |
  |:-----|:------:|------:|
  | L    | C      | R     |
}

// Images
@doc {
  # Images

  Inline images use standard Markdown syntax:

  ![Alt text for image](./images/example.png)

  Images with titles:

  ![Logo](./images/logo.png "Company Logo")
}

// Multi-line content with triple quotes
@doc {
  content: '''
    # Using Triple Quotes

    For longer content, you can use triple-quoted strings.
    This preserves formatting and makes the OSF file more readable.

    - Item 1
    - Item 2
    - Item 3

    This is especially useful when you have content that
    spans many lines.
  ''';
}
